dataset.title: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities, Delta Plant Communities 1988-2007, Cedar River Municipal Watershed, King County, WA

abstract.para: Seattle Public Utilities manages the Cedar River Municipal Watershed and reservoir, Chester Morse Lake, to provide drinking water for 1.6 million residents in the greater Seattle area. The Cedar and Rex rivers are the two largest tributaries to Chester Morse Lake and flow over broad, low gradient deltas. The deltas have mostly fine sediments, sinuous low-flow channels, and an extensive wetland complex with aquatic, herbaceous, shrub, and forest components.

Delta plant communities were mapped in 1988, 1996, and 2007 using aerial photography. Plant communities were ground-truthed and boundaries and classification of polygons were corrected where errors were evident. Plant communities were classified into major structural classes, including herbaceous, shrub, deciduous forest, mixed deciduous/conifer forest, and conifer forest. A system of permanent plots was established on the Cedar and Rex river deltas and measured in 1988, 1996, and 2007. Transects comprised of sample plots every 25 meters were surveyed for herbaceous and shrub cover. An additional transect was established in the floodplain of the Cedar River through mixed deciduous and conifer forest to measure tree diameter at breast height and species.
This package is complete, and the data were analyzed to evaluate the potential for future adverse impacts to delta plant communities resulting from changes to the reservoir operating regime.

description.para: Chester Morse Lake Daily Elevations: Water levels in Chester Morse Lake were measured daily by Seattle Public Utilities staff at the Overflow Dike (and previous to 1988 at the Crib Dam) since 1940. Water levels are recorded to the nearest .01 foot and converted to meters for analysis.

Plant Community Mapping: Plant communities were mapped from aerial photographs taken in 1989, 1996, and 2007. Polygons on draft maps were ground-truthed by comparing mapped polygons to distribution of plant communities while walking through the delta areas. Boundaries and classification of polygons were corrected where errors were evident. Plant communities were classified into major structural classes, including herbaceous, shrub, deciduous forest, mixed deciduous/conifer forest, and conifer forest.

Transects Species Cover: Species A system of permanent plots was established on the Cedar and Rex river deltas in 1987. Plots were aligned in transects perpendicular to the delta shoreline and extended from mudflat at the lower elevation end through sedge-dominated meadows and willow-dominated shrub vegetation at the higher elevation end. Three transects were established in each of the two river deltas, with the Cedar delta transects ranging from 275 to 450 meters and the Rex delta transects ranging from 200 to 250 meters in length. The sample plots along the transects were located at 25 meter intervals and marked with PVC pipe. Plots were sampled in the same locations in 1988, 1996, and 2007. Herbaceous cover was estimated within a square 1 m2 plot frame, placed with its southwest corner a distance of 3 meters from the PVC pipe perpendicular to and on the north side of the transect. Shrub cover was measured in a circular plot with a radius of 5 meters centered on the southwest corner of the herb plot. Plant cover (vertical projection of leaves [herbs] or canopy [shrubs]) was estimated as the percent of plot surface area for each species present. Plant cover of all species present was recorded as one of the 10 cover classes in 1988 and in percent cover in 1996 and 2007. The 1988 cover classes were defined as 0, 0-.5, .5-1, 1-2, 2-4, 4-8, 8-16, 16-32, 32-64, and 64-100%. For the purposes of direct gradient analysis, the midpoints of the cover classes were used as abundance values for the 1988 measurements.

Plots were sampled in late summer to early fall, when Chester Morse Lake water levels were near their lowest of the year. Only plots exposed from inundation at the lowest water of the sampled year were measured.

Plot Elevations: Plot elevations were surveyed in 1993 and 2007 following standard surveying methods using a surveyors level and stadia rod. In 1993, elevations were taken at 50-meter intervals at every other plot, while in 2007 elevations were taken at 25-meter intervals at each plot location. The 1993 measurements were used for both 1988 and 1996 plot data. Plot elevations were established in relation to the Seattle Datum, which is the datum used for the long-term water level records for Chester Morse Lake. The Seattle Datum is 11.15 feet (3.4 meters) above that of the NAVD 1988 datum.

abstract.para: As part of the Cedar Permanent Dead Storage Project evaluation, the City modeled the new reservoir operating regime, make comparisons to past conditions, and evaluated the potential for future adverse impacts to the delta plant communities (including floodplains). In addition, the City evaluated the results of the delta vegetation monitoring project (Raedeke 1998) in relation to new reservoir fill and drawdown regimes predicted by modeling exercises.

dataTable.entityDescription: Transects were established in the Cedar and Rex delta for sampling herbaceous and shrub cover. Sampling plots along transects were located at 25-meter intervals. Plots were measured in the same locations in 1988, 1996, and 2007. Herbaceous cover was estimated within a 1-m2 plot frame, placed with its southwest corner a distance of 3-meters from the PVC pipe perpendicular to and on the north side of the transect. Shrub cover was measured in a circular plot with a radius of 5-meters centered on the southwest corner of the herb plot. Plant cover of leaves or canopy was estimated as the percent of plot surface area for each species present. Plots were sampled in late summer to early fall, when Chester Morse Lakes water levels were near their lowest of the year. Only plots exposed from inundation at the lowest water of the sampled year were measured.
